					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Tepples' "static" GBA demo <em>proves that the GBA display is interlaced the same way as the GBC display, with alternate lines being drawn darker and lighter in each frame.</em><br /><br />Can I have more details about this ?<br />When running the test on my GBA I see horizontal lines that aren't visible in Visual Boy Advance. The programm is flickering blue and yellow, and on the GBA it appers like one pixel out of two is blue and the other yellow. The results are the same on my DS, and that for both screens.</div><br />It's a common trick to reduce motion blurring on an LCD: draw pixels darker in alternate frames. The GBC, GBA, and DS screens do it by scanline; I've seen LCDs for PC do it in sort of a checkerboard fashion.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Does that means even lines on the GBC/GBA/DS are refresehed one frame and odd lines another ? I bet many scrolling backgrounds would look terrible if that were the case (might be wrong).</div><br />I've seen subtle combing artifacts on horizontally scrolling backgrounds in some games.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">(PS : Tepples to show a 6 pixel wide font on the GBA why not use a bitmap mode instead of wasting mode-7 scaling for that ?)</div><br />It takes a lot more cycles to update the 48 pixels of a bitmap than to update one character cell, even with the read-modify-write that the GBA's 16-bit VRAM bus requires. That's one reason why games use tiled modes in the first place, and why PocketNES and Goomba map emulated system tiles to GBA tiles instead of doing a full software rendering like Lameboy does. Besides, on the GBA, mode 1 still has two "text" backgrounds; the extended rotation modes (3-5) do not unless you're on a DS booted into DS mode.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Would be great if someone would release a LCD filter emulating this behavior, GBC/GBA/DS equivalent of NTSC filter.</div>
<br />Pixel ordering (RGB on one of the original DS's screens, or BGR on GBA, GBA SP, DS Lite, and the DS's other screen) would also be useful for a 2x-4x upscaler. But most new desktop PCs and all laptops come with LCD monitors, and the video processing inside a monitor might interfere. The closest you can get without requiring a CRT or plasma monitor is emulating the screwed up black level and gamma (see "GAMMA" screen in Static).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

