						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's a common trick to reduce motion blurring on an LCD: draw pixels darker in alternate frames. The GBC, GBA, and DS screens do it by scanline<br /></div><br />I still don't understand the trick or the origin of the horizontal lines artifacts.</div><br />I don't know <em>how</em> darkening alternate pixels improves apparent response time; I just know <em>that</em> it works.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">It takes a lot more cycles to update the 48 pixels of a bitmap than to update one character cell</div><br />The GBA doesn't have a 16MHz processor for nothing.</div><br />But that still doesn't mean one should squander it. Saving CPU on your text routines can free up time for other routines or for sleeping in a low-power state.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I don't see much difference between my PC which is connected to a CRT screen and the other one who has a LCD. Scrolling text doesn't look very good on the LCD, but there is no noticeable motion blur, and the results of your flickering tests doesn't look like the real hardware at all (no horizontal lines, just flickering yellow/blue).</div>
<br />In that case, it might take high-speed cameras to gain a handle on what the GBA LCD is really showing at any given moment, just as it took an oscilloscope to see what signal the NES was creating.</div>

