					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's a common trick to reduce motion blurring on an LCD: draw pixels darker in alternate frames. The GBC, GBA, and DS screens do it by scanline<br /></div><br />I still don't understand the trick or the origin of the horizontal lines artifacts.</div><br />I don't know <em>how</em> darkening alternate pixels improves apparent response time; I just know <em>that</em> it works.</div>
<br />The same way interlacing will apparently double the framerate of a low-framerate screen, I'd imagine. Update the screen slower, motion blur is reduced greatly; many older gameboy-phat games use this technique, i.e. why many games have "choppy" movement in comparison to the smooth movement of the nes. Offset the refreshing of the scanlines, and you pretty much get interlacing. The screen looks like it's updating at 60hz, but each scanline is actually getting the 'major' update every 30hz.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />-Drag</div>
